\begin_layout Section

\series bold
Energy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You drive the LHS of the string with SHM.
 You could imagine that as you pull up from 
\begin_inset Formula $y=0$
\end_inset

 this would not only stretch the string, maximally, but would also be the
 point where the string is moving the most.
 Moreover, at exactly 
\begin_inset Formula $y=y_{m}$
\end_inset

 you could imagine that you are no longer stretching the string and at exactly
 that point there is no kinetic energy i.e.
 a single particle at the peak of its SHM would be motionless.
 This reasoning about the kinetic energy follows from the same reasoning
 while analyzing SHM.
 You could then intuitvly reason about the stretching by saying that well
 if the string's not moving its not being stretched, so the Energy associated
 with its motion must track with the energy placed into the elastic potential
 energy of the string i.e.
 its stretching.
 Formally, consider a small string element of mass 
\begin_inset Formula $dm$
\end_inset

 over a section 
\begin_inset Formula $dx$
\end_inset

.
 Now consider the differential slice of the KE associated with its transverse
 (up and down) motion.
 Remember we are driving the wave with SHM so it is a sine wave.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
dK=.5dm(\frac{\partial y}{\partial t})^{2}=.5(\mu dx)y_{m}^{2}w^{2}\cos^{2}(kx-wt)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now as you might have guessed, divide both sides by a small time differential
 to get a rate at which kinetic energy is transfered.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{dK}{dt}=.5\mu vy_{m}^{2}w^{2}\cos^{2}(kx-wt)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taking the average yields one half of the above because the average over
 the square cosine is one half.
 However we wish to analzye the total energy transfer which would include
 the elastic potential energy.
 But since we are driving this wave with SHM, we know that the average potential
 energy equals that of the kinetic as over time, kinetic and potential average
 to exactly half that of the total energy in SHM.
 Thus the rate at which total energy is transferred and the thus the average
 power is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P_{avg}=.5\mu vy_{m}^{2}w^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

