\begin_layout Section
Deriving the 1D Wave Equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First just accept that 
\begin_inset Formula $v^{2}=\frac{T}{\mu}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is the tension in the string and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is the linear density.
 Moving on, consider a small slice of string 
\begin_inset Formula $dx$
\end_inset

 with mass 
\begin_inset Formula $dm=\mu dx$
\end_inset

, at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Now there is some constant tension 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 in this string that acts tangent to the string at all times.
 Now consider this tension at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and at the point 
\begin_inset Formula $x+dx$
\end_inset

.
 As the wave passes through the point 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, it increases or decreases the slope of the tangent line at that point,
 causing a slight difference in the tension.
 Thus the acceleration upward or downward that our slice feels is just the
 net difference of the tension at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 with the tension at 
\begin_inset Formula $x+dx$
\end_inset

.
 Since the tension is tangant to the rope, the net force is just the difference
 in the slope of the tangent line between 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x+dx$
\end_inset

 (scaled of course for the magnitude of the tension).
 Using Newtons law we can get a differential equation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F=T\frac{dy}{dx}(x+dx)-T\frac{dy}{dx}(x)=\mu dx\frac{d^{2}y}{dt^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{T}{\mu}\frac{\frac{dy}{dx}(x+dx)-\frac{dy}{dx}(x)}{dx}=\frac{d^{2}y}{dt^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can clearly see that as we take limit of the length of our differential
 going to zero, we just get the second space derivative on the left.
 So,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d^{2}y}{dt^{2}}=v^{2}\frac{d^{2}y}{dx^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Side Note, 
\series default
this physical intuition gives us an interesting way to look at the second
 derivative operator.
 That is the second derivative tells us how much a point differs from the
 average of its two neighbors.
 So consider three points, 
\begin_inset Formula $x-dx$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x+dx$
\end_inset

.
 Now the second order differential approximation is as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d^{2}u}{dx^{2}}=\frac{u(x+dx)-2u(x)+u(x-dx)}{dx^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using our above reasoning we can right this as the differnce betwen the
 slopes of two tangant lines
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
u(x+dx)-2u(x)+u(x-dx)=(u(x+dx)-u(x))-(u(x)-u(x-dx))
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, using this intuition we can think of the second derivative operator
 as measuring how much a point differs from the average of its two neighbors.
 Inuitively, if the tangent lines are the same at both ends (and thus the
 tension difference is 0), then the middle point lies on the line connecting
 them and thus the net acceleration is 0 (i.e.
 the acceleration is 0).
 However, if there is a difference in the tangent lines (tension), 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x+dx)-u(x)$
\end_inset

 differs from 
\begin_inset Formula $u(x)-u(x-dx)$
\end_inset

, thus there is a net force on the at 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 As shown below this is equivalent to the point x differing from the average
 of the two points around.
 Which again is equivalent to it not lying on the line connecting the two
 points around it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{u(x+dx)+u(x-dx)}{2}-u(x)=\frac{u(x+dx)+u(x-dx)-2u(x)}{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So we get an interesting way of looking at the wave equation.
 It says that looking at some line segement, the acceleration that line
 segment feels is proportional to how far displaced that point is from the
 line connecting the two points to its left and right.
\end_layout

