\begin_layout Section
Interference and Phasors
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose you have two waves on the same medium, then the overal wave is just
 the superposition of the two: 
\begin_inset Formula $y(x,t)=y_{1}(x,t)+y_{2}(x,t)$
\end_inset

.
 Consider two waves of equal amplitude that differ by some phase 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

.
 Then the resulting wave is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y(x,t)=y_{m}(\sin(kx-wt)+\sin(kx-wt+\phi))
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y(x,t)=2y_{m}\cos(.5\phi)\sin(kx-wt+.5\phi)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus the resulting wave is simpy a sin wave whose amplitude depends on how
 in phase the two contributing waves are.
 But what if the two waves do not have the same amplitudes, but still have
 the same temporal and spatial frequency and are possibly shifted in phase?
 That is where phasors come into play.
 Phasors seem a bit silly, just use Euler's formula)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y_{1}(x,t)=y_{1m}\sin(kx-wt)=\frac{1}{2i}(e^{i\xi}-e^{-i\xi})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
y_{2}(x,t)=y_{2m}\sin(kx-wt+\phi)=\frac{1}{2i}(e^{i\xi+i\phi}-e^{-i\xi-i\phi})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(y_{1}+y_{2})(x,t)=\frac{1}{2i}(e^{i\xi}(1+e^{i\phi})-e^{-i\xi}(1-e^{-i\phi}))
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $\xi=kx-wt$
\end_inset

.
 So let 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{i\alpha}=(1+e^{i\phi})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{-i\beta}=(1-e^{-i\phi})$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(y_{1}+y_{2})(x,t)=\frac{1}{2i}(e^{i\xi+i\alpha}-e^{-i\xi}(1-e^{-i\phi-i\beta}))
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now multipy and divide by 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{(\beta-\alpha)i/2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(y_{1}+y_{2})(x,t)=\frac{e^{i(\alpha-\beta)/2}}{2i}(e^{i\xi+\alpha i/2+\beta i/2}-e^{-i\xi}(1-e^{-i\phi-\beta i/2-\alpha i/2}))
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
(y_{1}+y_{2})(x,t)=y_{m}'\sin(kx-wt+\gamma)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $y'_{m}=e^{i(\alpha-\beta)/2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=\frac{\alpha+\beta}{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

